    <div style="basic">
        <p begin="00:00:00.000" end="00:00:05.480" tts:direction="ltr">Hello, visitors. We are on to the second
<br />principle of design,</p>
        <p begin="00:00:05.480" end="00:00:08.500" tts:direction="ltr">and that is the idea of contrast.</p>
        <p begin="00:00:08.500" end="00:00:10.760" tts:direction="ltr">We're going to address size,</p>
        <p begin="00:00:10.760" end="00:00:15.480" tts:direction="ltr">shape, color, and typography. Let's dive
<br />in.</p>
        <p begin="00:00:15.570" end="00:00:18.050" tts:direction="ltr">When it comes to size,</p>
        <p begin="00:00:18.050" end="00:00:20.050" tts:direction="ltr">it's important to recognize there are</p>
        <p begin="00:00:20.050" end="00:00:22.370" tts:direction="ltr">certain chart types that do this better
<br />than other.</p>
        <p begin="00:00:22.370" end="00:00:25.190" tts:direction="ltr">I'm giving you an example of a tree map.</p>
        <p begin="00:00:25.190" end="00:00:29.050" tts:direction="ltr">Tree maps really do show between size and
<br />also</p>
        <p begin="00:00:29.050" end="00:00:33.710" tts:direction="ltr">color the amount of the data that they
<br />have.</p>
        <p begin="00:00:33.710" end="00:00:37.470" tts:direction="ltr">But tree maps aren't the only way we can
<br />show size.</p>
        <p begin="00:00:37.470" end="00:00:38.870" tts:direction="ltr">Clearly, if it's larger,</p>
        <p begin="00:00:38.870" end="00:00:42.340" tts:direction="ltr">there's more data, if it's smaller,
<br />there's less data.</p>
        <p begin="00:00:42.340" end="00:00:46.310" tts:direction="ltr">There's also bubble charts where the
<br />larger the circle,</p>
        <p begin="00:00:46.310" end="00:00:48.170" tts:direction="ltr">then the more data, the smaller.</p>
        <p begin="00:00:48.170" end="00:00:52.910" tts:direction="ltr">We can again to use our natural instincts
<br />that we've learned in terms of size.</p>
        <p begin="00:00:52.910" end="00:00:56.150" tts:direction="ltr">But what we have the United States,</p>
        <p begin="00:00:56.150" end="00:00:59.490" tts:direction="ltr">where we have all of these different
<br />shapes,</p>
        <p begin="00:00:59.490" end="00:01:02.430" tts:direction="ltr">but they don't truly represent maybe size.</p>
        <p begin="00:01:02.430" end="00:01:05.410" tts:direction="ltr">Depends on the size. If I'm doing course
<br />land,</p>
        <p begin="00:01:05.410" end="00:01:09.590" tts:direction="ltr">then of course, Alaska should be gigantic.</p>
        <p begin="00:01:09.590" end="00:01:12.065" tts:direction="ltr">But if I'm doing population,</p>
        <p begin="00:01:12.065" end="00:01:15.000" tts:direction="ltr">Alaska would be the very smallest because
<br />I believe</p>
        <p begin="00:01:15.000" end="00:01:18.180" tts:direction="ltr">there's only about one half million people
<br />who live in Alaska.</p>
        <p begin="00:01:18.180" end="00:01:22.600" tts:direction="ltr">Size can and should align with your goal.</p>
        <p begin="00:01:22.600" end="00:01:26.900" tts:direction="ltr">If you have something that is larger and
<br />something that's smaller,</p>
        <p begin="00:01:26.900" end="00:01:29.700" tts:direction="ltr">there should be that pre attentive
<br />attribute</p>
        <p begin="00:01:29.700" end="00:01:32.860" tts:direction="ltr">that larger means more and smaller means
<br />less.</p>
        <p begin="00:01:32.860" end="00:01:35.680" tts:direction="ltr">Make sure that you're matching those.</p>
        <p begin="00:01:35.680" end="00:01:39.780" tts:direction="ltr">That will happen as a default in the tree
<br />map and in the bubble chart.</p>
        <p begin="00:01:39.780" end="00:01:45.100" tts:direction="ltr">But sometimes we can layer multiple
<br />dimensions on a chart and we</p>
        <p begin="00:01:45.100" end="00:01:51.090" tts:direction="ltr">can confuse our user if we're not aligning
<br />size with what the insight is.</p>
        <p begin="00:01:51.090" end="00:01:54.330" tts:direction="ltr">Instead of using the traditional map,</p>
        <p begin="00:01:54.330" end="00:01:56.450" tts:direction="ltr">and if I was wanting to show maybe</p>
